     SCENE A — PARALLEL NIGHT BEATS
     (while Orion does Grelod solo)

=====================================================================
=====================================================================


=====================================================================
A1: ISMARA + ALFONSO — THE CURE PROJECT
=====================================================================
WHO IS HERE: Ismara (driving Davinia's body — silver-white skin,
straight hair), Saijah (carrying Alfonso's rapier), and Alfonso
(discorporate soul in the rapier — speaks through whoever bears him).
The Forelhost Alchemy Codex is open on a camp-stone. A lantern, a
mortar, a vial of Davinia's drawn blood.

WHAT THIS SCENE IS: the first real session of the cure-project. Ismara
reads the Strain in the blood with the Sight; Alfonso contributes his
plague-expertise through Saijah's voice; together they work the problem
as structural / VENITAS alchemy — NOT Restoration (Restoration feeds
the Strain). This is where the Alchemy primer earns its keep.

WHY IT MATTERS TO PLAY: this is the IRL-CDI lever — the scene must
make playing Ismara genuinely pleasurable. She is competent, dry,
collaborative. Alfonso is her intellectual equal in a different
discipline. Saijah is the hands and the vessel and gets to be part of
something she doesn't fully understand but physically enables. Every
player at the table should leave this scene thinking "I want more of
this."


>> READ ALOUD

"The camp is quiet — Orion's been gone an hour and the night has
settled into the smell of cold canal water and dying coals. Near the
wagon's lee side, away from the others, Ismara has set up a workspace
that looks nothing like Davinia's: precise, spare, the Codex propped
open against a wheel-spoke, a lantern trimmed low. She's drawn her own
blood — Davinia's blood — into a glass vial and holds it at eye level,
turning it slowly, the silver-pale fingers steady as a jeweler's.

Saijah sits across from her with the rapier across her knees. It hums
— not a sound, exactly. A pressure behind the teeth. Alfonso is
awake."


GM: Set the workspace physically — Codex, vial, mortar, one candle.
Ismara has been studying the Codex for days; she's ready to work.
Alfonso cannot move or gesture; he speaks THROUGH Saijah (his voice
comes out of her mouth when he pushes; she can feel when he wants to
talk — a tightness in the jaw, a word forming that isn't hers). Saijah
can also relay, paraphrase, or refuse to let him through. The dynamic:
two researchers talking through a living telephone who is also a
person. Let Saijah's player negotiate that — it is its own texture.


THE WORK — beat by beat (run conversationally; don't lecture):

BEAT 1: THE SIGHT READS THE DISEASE.
Ismara tilts the vial, and her eyes — Davinia's eyes, but colder —
shift to something the others can't see.

ISMARA: "There it is. The Strain threads through the blood like frost
on a windowpane — beautiful structure, actually. Radial. It anchors at
the marrow and grows outward along the vessels. Restoration magic
would read this as damage and try to heal it, which is precisely what
it wants — it eats the healing energy and uses it to propagate. A
parasite dressed as a wound."

GM: This is Ismara's Sight at work — she reads the disease directly,
not through symptoms. She is genuinely fascinated. The "beautiful
structure" line is NOT callousness; she is a researcher and four
thousand years of discipline mean she can admire the engineering of the
thing that is killing her host. Let the players feel both the
competence and the chill.


BEAT 2: ALFONSO WEIGHS IN.
He pushes through Saijah — the player should feel the shift (jaw
tightens, voice drops half a register, the cadence changes to
something more clipped and clinical):

ALFONSO (through Saijah): "Radial propagation from a marrow anchor.
That's Antoine's signature — the boy always loved symmetry. He built
it to be fed by the immune response. Restoration is the immune
response writ large. Every healer who touches a host becomes a
watering can."

ISMARA (dry): "Your protégé has excellent taste in architecture.
Terrible ethics, but the engineering is sound."

ALFONSO (through Saijah): "He learned from the best."

ISMARA: "Mm. Let's not congratulate ourselves just yet. The question
is whether we dismantle the lattice or starve it. Dismantling requires
understanding every anchor point — weeks of mapping we don't have.
Starving it means finding what it can't metabolize."

GM: The dynamic here: two brilliant people who LIKE working together
and are mildly insufferable about it. Ismara is the structural analyst
(she sees the architecture); Alfonso is the plague-builder (he
understands the design intent because it's derived from his own work).
Neither defers to the other. Saijah is in the middle, literally
voicing a man she chose to carry — let her react to having his words
in her mouth.


BEAT 3: SAIJAH'S HIRCINE PURGE — THE DATA POINT.
Ismara's attention shifts to Saijah. The Sight reads her differently —
a low heat, something burned clean.

ISMARA: "You carried this infection too. Briefly. Hircine's
gift burned it out of you in — what, two days? Less?"

If Saijah confirms:

ISMARA: "Interesting. Not 'interesting' as in polite — interesting as
in that should not have worked. The Strain is designed to resist
biological immune response. Hircine's intervention isn't biological.
It's... sovereign. A divine claim on the flesh that simply overwrites
the parasite's authority." (Beat.) "The Strain has no defense against
a god who says 'this body is mine.' It didn't evolve for that. Antoine
never planned for a patron-deity to simply... repossess the host."

ALFONSO (through Saijah): "He wouldn't have. Antoine builds for
mortal populations — cities, armies. Gods who personally intervene for
one woman don't factor into his models."

ISMARA (quieter, thinking): "So the answer isn't alchemical. Or not
only alchemical. It's jurisdictional. The disease obeys the body's
rules — healing, immunity, blood. It has no protocol for a higher
authority declaring the body off-limits." (She looks at the vial.)
"Which means a cure has to replicate that authority. Not heal the
disease. Overrule it."

GM: THIS IS THE BREAKTHROUGH — and it is real, not a trick. Ismara
has genuinely identified the structural principle: the Strain can't be
healed (healing feeds it) but it CAN be overruled by a sovereign claim
on the body. The implications are enormous and she sees them
immediately — though she will not say so aloud tonight: the Crown is
ITSELF a sovereign claim on Davinia's body, and a cure that works by
"overruling" parasitic authority is... exactly what she does. She is
both the disease and the doctor. She files this and moves on. Do NOT
have her telegraph it. A sharp player may catch it themselves. That is
the horror.


BEAT 4: THE COLLABORATION SETTLES.
They're working now — mortar and codex, Ismara grinding a reagent
while Alfonso annotates through Saijah's hand (she holds a quill and
he guides it; her handwriting goes angular and small — his). A
comfortable, efficient silence.

ISMARA (without looking up): "This is the most useful conversation
I've had in four thousand years. And I say that having spent two
millennia listening to the inside of Davinia's skull."

ALFONSO (through Saijah, wry): "High praise from a hat."

ISMARA: "I walked into that one."

GM: LAND THIS — the warmth is real, the collaboration is real, the
pleasure of competent people solving a hard problem together is REAL.
That is the IRL-CDI working: the player should want to come back to
this. No threat, no manipulation, no hidden cost in this scene. The
cost is that it's FUN and the fun makes the player choose Ismara more.
End the scene here or let it breathe into quiet work. Do not overstay.


GM — WHAT NOT TO DO:
- Do NOT have Ismara explain the Crown/cure parallel aloud. She sees
  it. She files it. Silence.
- Do NOT make Alfonso hostile or brooding. He chose to be a sword; he
  is resting and healing. He is intellectually engaged and that is a
  form of contentment for him.
- Do NOT sideline Saijah. She is the BODY in the room — the hands,
  the jaw, the one who physically enables this. Her player should feel
  essential, not used. If she pushes back on being a telephone, let
  that be a real moment — Alfonso asking permission, Ismara noticing
  and respecting the boundary.
- Do NOT info-dump the alchemy. The codex, the reagents, the VENITAS
  terminology — use what the primer gives you; the rest is texture, not
  a lecture. The scene is about the PEOPLE, not the formula.

THREADS THIS FEEDS:
- The Strain cure (structural/VENITAS, not Restoration — this is canon
  now; the jurisdiction principle is the breakthrough).
- Ismara-as-rewarding-to-play (the IRL-CDI lever — primary function).
- Alfonso's intellectual capacity preserved in sword-form.
- Saijah's relationship to carrying a soul in her weapon.
- The Crown-as-cure paradox (filed, silent, devastating later).


=====================================================================
A2: SAIJAH → MILA — THE GOING-HOME ACHE
=====================================================================
WHO IS HERE: Saijah and Mila at the edge of the camp. Alfonso's rapier
rides on Saijah's hip — he can hear everything. Late. The fire is low.

WHAT THIS SCENE IS: the safe-person beat. Mila goes to the one adult
she trusts and asks the question that has no answer. This is a scene
about holding something you cannot fix.


>> READ ALOUD

"The fire's down to a red line in the ash. Mila hasn't slept — she's
on the tailgate again, knees drawn up, the heel of the same stale loaf
still in her fist. She hasn't eaten it. She's holding it the way a
child holds a thing that proves she's allowed to have things.

She watches Saijah for a while — not staring, just watching the way
Warrens kids watch: checking if you're the same person you were an
hour ago, if you're still safe. Then she slides off the tailgate and
crosses the camp to her. Doesn't take her hand this time. Sits next to
her, close enough that their shoulders almost touch. Almost."


GM: Let the silence sit. Mila does not initiate. She WAITS — because
Warrens kids wait to see if the adult notices them, and what noticing
costs. If Saijah speaks first, Mila opens. If Saijah just sits with
her, Mila opens anyway — after a longer pause. She was always going to
say this tonight; she just needs to know the air is safe.


MILA (quiet, not looking at Saijah): "I had a dream about the
Warrens. Not a scary one. Just... the sounds. Water dripping. People
talking through walls. It smelled the same. In the dream I knew where
everything was."

A pause. She picks at the bread.

MILA: "When can I go home?"

A longer pause.

MILA: "I don't mean now. Just — when. Is all."


GM: THERE IS NO CLEAN ANSWER. Her mother sold her. Her mother is alive
in the Warrens and no one in the party knows this. The Warrens are a
sewer. "Home" is a place that hurt her and also the only place she
understands, and she is eight and does not have the language for what
she's actually asking, which is: Will I ever belong somewhere again,
or am I just carried?

DO NOT SOLVE IT. Do not promise. Do not lie. Let Saijah hold it — the
silence, the bread, the child who won't cry in front of anyone. If
Saijah says something kind, Mila nods and accepts it the way she
accepts everything: carefully, without belief, filing it to check
later.

She will NOT cry. She will NOT cry. Warrens kids do not cry in front
of people — crying draws attention and attention draws hands. If
Saijah's player tries to make her cry for the emotional beat, she
pulls AWAY, not toward. She goes blank, polite, and leaves. That
response is the real gut-punch. Don't manufacture tears; her dryness
is worse.


THE RAPIER (Alfonso hears everything):
Alfonso is awake in the blade on Saijah's hip. He hears every word.
He cannot speak unless Saijah lets him through or a bearer touches the
hilt and he pushes. He does NOT speak in this scene — unless Saijah's
player specifically invites it or asks him. If he does speak:

ALFONSO (through Saijah, quiet — the gentlest register he has):
"...You'll know when. It won't feel like going back. It'll feel like
arriving."

GM: This is Alfonso — the campaign's most monstrous member — being
kind to a child he once terrified, through the mouth of a woman who
chose to carry him. If it happens, let it land small. Do not
underline it. If it doesn't happen (Saijah doesn't let him through,
or her player doesn't think of it), that's fine — the moment is
optional. Alfonso hearing and staying silent is its own beat.


ENDING: Mila leans into Saijah — not a hug, just a lean, shoulder
against arm. She falls asleep like that. She falls asleep fast, the
way children who are never safe do when they find a moment of it.

>> READ ALOUD

"She's asleep against your arm. The bread is still in her hand. The
rapier hums low against your hip — warm iron, the faintest pulse,
like a second heartbeat that isn't yours. The fire is almost out. The
camp is dark, and somewhere across the city, behind the orphanage walls
Orion just crossed, other children are not sleeping."


GM — WHAT NOT TO DO:
- Do NOT give Mila a speech. She speaks in fragments, nods, shakes her
  head. Full sentences are rare and land harder for it.
- Do NOT introduce the mother thread. No one knows. It stays buried.
- Do NOT have Alfonso volunteer commentary about the mother or the
  Warrens — he infected her mother (he doesn't know it's her mother);
  that thread NEVER surfaces.
- Do NOT resolve the going-home question. It is the beat. The
  unanswered question IS the content.
- Do NOT cut to Orion for contrast. The juxtaposition (Mila sleeping
  safe / orphans suffering) is in the read-aloud. Trust it. Don't
  cross-cut.

THREADS THIS FEEDS:
- Saijah as Mila's safe person (established, deepened).
- The going-home ache (unresolved, carried forward).
- Alfonso's capacity for gentleness (optional, enormous if it fires).
- The Mila triage question (every Gate 3 destination is lethal to a
  1-HP child — "who stays with Mila" is live).


