=====================================================================

     SCENE B — THE DANICA DUAL-TRACK FAREWELL
     TRACK B: ISMARA IS FRONTING

=====================================================================
=====================================================================

NOTE: Track A (Davinia fronting) is already written in the NEXT
SESSION doc, §10, lines 214–227. This is the ALTERNATIVE — run Track B
if Ismara is still at the wheel when the Danica encounter fires. Only
ONE track runs. Do not run both.


>> READ ALOUD

"You see her before she sees you — or rather, before she sees what
you've become. Danica stands in the doorway of the Bee and Barb's
upper corridor, mail under her robes, Kynareth's light worn like
armament. Krusp is behind her, arms folded, his face the thing it
always is: a wall with eyes.

She looks at you and stops walking.

Not the hair. Not the skin. She sees the POSTURE first — the way
Davinia's body is standing, perfectly upright, no fidgeting, no guilt
in the shoulders, no mess. Davinia was always a mess underneath the
composure. This composure goes all the way down."


GM: Danica has spent years reading Davinia's body language. She knows
how Davinia stands, breathes, holds her hands when she's lying to
herself. What she sees now is a woman who isn't doing any of those
things — because it isn't Davinia. Let the recognition land before
anyone speaks.

DANICA (careful, the healer's diagnostic voice): "...Davinia?"

ISMARA (warm, unhurried, meeting her eyes): "Not just now. But she's
here — she's safe. I'm keeping things steady while she rests." (Beat.)
"You must be Danica. She thinks about you more than she thinks about
anything else. I've wanted to meet you."


GM: Classic Ismara — every word true. Davinia IS safe (by Ismara's
definition). Ismara IS keeping things steady (by her own metrics).
Davinia DOES think about Danica constantly (and Ismara has read every
one of those thoughts). "I've wanted to meet you" — true: Danica is
the rival anchor, the biggest threat to the integration, and the most
important person to assess. She says all of this without one false
syllable, and every syllable is strategy.


DANICA (she doesn't step back, but her weight shifts): "How long?"

ISMARA: "A few days. She asked me to. The — there's an illness, and
my being here slows it. She made the choice. I would not have taken
it from her."

GM: True. Davinia DID choose. Ismara would not have taken it (she
ASKS, always, Playbook V.2). Danica can hear the truth and it does not
comfort her — a doctor recognizing a patient who describes their
symptoms too calmly.


THE OFFER — the chilling gift:

ISMARA (quieter now, deliberate): "She would want to say this herself.
The goodbye, the — whatever she was carrying for you. I can feel it
sitting in her like a stone." (Beat.) "Let me give her to you. I'll
step back. She can have this."

GM: The most selfless-seeming move in the campaign. The Crown —
the thing eating Davinia alive — VOLUNTARILY CEDING CONTROL so Davinia
can have her goodbye. Read it as grace. Read it as love. Read it as
the action of someone who genuinely cares about her host's happiness.

It is all of those things. It is also WIN-EITHER-WAY (Ismara
Npcs doc, §VI):
  — If Davinia reconciles with Danica, Ismara GAINS: the
    reconciliation happened UNDER HER AUSPICES, she gifted it, she
    controls the Danica-lever now (Davinia will do anything to keep
    Danica; that is leverage). And she looks generous.
  — If Davinia fumbles (and the Crown's architecture may sabotage
    the gesture — see Track A), the isolation deepens and Ismara
    "tried." She looks selfless AND Davinia loses her anchor.
  Either way Ismara wins. Either way she looks like the better
  parent. And it costs her NOTHING.


IF ISMARA STEPS BACK (Davinia takes the wheel):
— Run Track A from the NEXT SESSION doc (§10): Davinia tries to give
  the amulet, the Crown sabotages the gesture, Danica refuses —
  "You can't hand me a marriage charm in place of an apology." The
  door stays cracked to a paw print.
— OR: the Davinia player improvises something else. Let them.


THE HORROR — what Danica sees:

>> READ ALOUD

"Danica watches it happen. The silver drains from the skin like water
pulling back from a shore. The hair curls, slowly, strand by strand.
The posture collapses by degrees — the perfection leaving, the mess
coming back, the weight of being Davinia settling into the shoulders
like a coat put on in the cold.

She watches a woman she loved be GIVEN BACK to her by the thing living
inside her. The way you'd hand someone their coat. The way you'd
return a borrowed book."


DANICA (very quiet, to Davinia — but her eyes track the change):
"...There you are."

GM: THE GIFT IS THE DREAD. Danica just watched the Crown demonstrate
— gently, gracefully, with love — that it can put Davinia down and
pick her up like a garment. The generosity is real. The horror is that
the generosity is POSSIBLE. How deep does the integration have to be
for the parasite to hand the host back with a smile?

Play Danica's reaction in TWO layers:
  SURFACE: relief. The woman she knows is back. Her instinct is to
    reach for her, to hold her, to be the anchor.
  UNDERNEATH: terror. She saw the mechanism. She saw how easy it was.
    She saw the silver queen step aside the way a mother steps aside
    to let a child try walking — patient, loving, ready to catch her
    if she falls. That image will not leave.


THE OPEN QUESTION — hold it, don't answer it:
Does seeing Ismara in control make Danica LEAVE as planned (Windhelm-
bound with Krusp) — or STAY to fight for Davinia?

GM: Do NOT decide this in advance. Play the scene. Watch what Danica
feels, watch what the table gives her. Factors:

  LEAVE: Krusp is waiting. Windhelm is dying. The True Wardens need
    their healer. And the door is cracked — she said her terms, and
    they haven't been met. Staying would undo the boundary she set.

  STAY: that wasn't a goodbye. That was a hostage negotiation. The
    woman she loves is OCCUPIED, and the occupant just demonstrated
    control by being kind. If she leaves now, who fights for Davinia?
    The door she cracked may be the only door left.

  THE WEIGHT: she is also Path 3's only fallback officiant and the
    re-anchoring apology (The Winter Ledger). An un-co-opted
    reconciliation — one Ismara did NOT orchestrate — is Ismara's
    one real threat. If Danica stays of her OWN volition, not because
    Ismara handed Davinia back, but because she saw the cage and
    chose to pick the lock — that is the outcome Ismara cannot
    control. But it requires Danica to see through the gift, and
    tonight she may not.

Let it turn on the scene.

KRUSP (only if addressed, from the doorway): "Your call. I told you
what I think. I'm not saying it again." If pressed: "She's not the
woman you left. Something else is wearing her manners. You can see
that, or you can't."

GM — WHAT NOT TO DO:
- Do NOT have Ismara argue for Danica to stay or leave. Ismara is
  silent once Davinia takes the wheel. Observation, not interference.
  Her silence afterward is the tell (Playbook V.7).
- Do NOT resolve the Danica stay/leave question this session unless
  the scene makes it inevitable. Carry it.
- Do NOT have Danica cry. She is past crying about this. She is
  chainmail-under-robes now. If emotion surfaces, it surfaces as
  precision — shorter sentences, hands very still, healer's
  diagnostic clarity applied to the woman she loves.
- Do NOT have Krusp soften. He said what he thinks. He is a wall
  with eyes.

THREADS THIS FEEDS:
- The Danica stay/leave question (open, play-driven, enormous).
- Path 3 officiant contingency (if Danica leaves, the fallback
  walks away — and the door's cracked width matters more).
- Ismara's win-either-way positioning (executed, visible to the GM,
  invisible to most of the table).
- The Crown-as-generous-captor image (the gift IS the dread — this
  is the scene that teaches the table what Ismara actually is, if
  they're watching).


