=====================================================================

     SCENE C — YLVA → ISMARA: THE COLLISION

=====================================================================
=====================================================================

WHO IS HERE: Ylva and Ismara (driving Davinia's body). Camp at night.
Ylva has been circling all evening, working up to approaching
"Davinia." She has NEVER MET Ismara. She does not know the silver-white
skin means a different person is home.

WHAT THIS SCENE IS: the first meeting between the werewolf pursuing
Davinia and the ancient intelligence wearing her. Three beats — one
arc: Repulsion → Dismissal → Resolve.


>> READ ALOUD

"Ylva's been watching her from across the camp for an hour. The silver
one. She's been telling herself it's the firelight, the late hour, a
trick of the cold — that the woman by the Codex is Davinia in a mood,
Davinia tired, Davinia being difficult the way she always is. But the
distance isn't helping. It's making it worse. The wrongness gets
LOUDER the longer she watches, like a sound just below hearing that
won't resolve into a note.

So she does what Ylva does: she stops thinking about it and walks
straight over."


=====================================================================
C1: REPULSION
=====================================================================

>> READ ALOUD

"Up close it hits her like walking into a cold room. The woman sitting
at the wagon wheel looks up, and everything Ylva's body knows about
hunting says WRONG. The skin is silver-pale and too smooth, like
something cast rather than grown. The hair hangs straight — Davinia's
hair curls, always, it fights itself, it's alive. This hair lies flat.
And the eyes — Davinia's eyes were always doing six things at once:
reading, worrying, calculating, flinching. These eyes do ONE thing.
They assess.

Ylva's hackles go up. Not a metaphor — the fine hair along her
forearms rises, the muscles in her shoulders bunch, and her jaw
tightens around a growl she doesn't let out. Every wolf-sense she has
is screaming: this is not prey. This is not pack. This is something
that SITS where a living thing should be."


YLVA (blunt, stopping three paces back — farther than she intended):
"...Davinia."

ISMARA (looks up from the Codex, unhurried, a measured smile):
"Close. You must be Ylva."

YLVA (the growl is in her voice now): "What do you mean, 'close'?"

ISMARA: "I mean I'm not Davinia. I'm Ismara. She's resting — I'm
minding things." (She tilts her head, studying Ylva the way she
studies everything — filing.) "She's mentioned you. The sparring
challenge, the wineskin. She was flattered, I think."

GM: Ismara is doing three things at once: (1) identifying herself
honestly (she never lies), (2) establishing that she has access to
Davinia's memories and feelings ("she was flattered"), and (3)
assessing Ylva as a variable. What she sees: a powerful, hot-blooded
werewolf running on instinct and want. She files Ylva under NOISE —
a physical creature beneath strategic notice. This is her canonical
blind spot (Npcs/Ismara §VI): Ylva's warmth is the one medicine that
slows the merger, and Ismara does not see it. The threat walks right
up and she waves it off.

YLVA (her weight shifts backward — not retreat, but her body refusing
to close the distance): "You're not her. You're — " (She can't name
it. She doesn't have the vocabulary for what the Sight is, what the
Crown is, what integration means. She has the vocabulary of a hunter,
and what her hunter's body is telling her is:) "You're cold. You're
not ALIVE the way she is."

ISMARA (a beat of genuine surprise — then, dry): "I'm four thousand
years old. Cold is a professional hazard."

GM: Ylva just said the most perceptive thing anyone has said about
Ismara, and she said it on instinct, not intelligence. "You're not
alive the way she is" — that is exactly right. Ismara is a
consciousness in a lattice driving a borrowed body; she is brilliant,
she is real, she is a person, but she is not ALIVE the way Davinia is
alive, messy and warm and chaotic and PRESENT. Ylva can feel the
difference because she is a creature of flesh and blood and heat, and
what she's standing in front of is a museum exhibit that breathes.

Ismara hears this and does not understand why it matters. That is the
blind spot.


=====================================================================
C2: DISMISSAL
=====================================================================

Ismara has taken Ylva's measure and found her... uncomplicated.

ISMARA (returning to the Codex, the audience over): "She'll be back
when the work is done. The illness needs managing, and I do that
better than she does — we agree on this. If you'd like to speak with
her, I can pass a message."

GM: The queen's dismissal. Not cruel — Ismara is never cruel without
purpose — just FINISHED. Ylva is a physical being with physical wants,
and Ismara has no category for that as a threat. She offers to pass a
message the way a secretary offers to take a call: efficiently, with
no intention of prioritizing it.

YLVA (stepping closer now, anger burning through the wrongness):
"I don't want to pass a MESSAGE. I want to talk to HER. Where is she?
What did you DO to her?"

ISMARA (calm, not looking up): "I didn't do anything to her. She
asked me to drive. I said yes. It's not complicated."

YLVA: "She wouldn't ask for that. She wouldn't just — hand herself
over — "

ISMARA (looks up, and for a moment the four-thousand-year-old
intelligence is fully present in Davinia's eyes): "She would. She did.
Because the alternative was a plague eating her from the inside out,
and she trusts me more than she trusts the disease." (Quieter, the
strategic vulnerability — one beat, deployed:) "I know what this looks
like. A stranger in your friend's body. But I am not her enemy. I am
the reason she is still HERE to come back to."

GM: EVERY WORD TRUE. The Strain IS real. Davinia DID choose. Ismara
IS the reason the Strain isn't progressing. And Ismara is not lying
